               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460921-name-1098" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460921-name-1098" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460921-name-1098" type="surname" value="CHURCHYARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460921-name-1098" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM CHURCHYARD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a tailor, and live at Clapham. About eleven or twelve o'clock, on the 17th of Sept., I left my shop, and when I re<lb></lb>turned I missed a waistcoat—I went out and met the prisoner—I asked if he had been at Clapham that morning—he said, "Yes"—I asked him what he had got in his pocket—he said, "A rule"—I found this black waistcoat in his pocket—it is mine.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When you came home, did you see anybody leave your shop? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I found the prisoner with the waistcoat, in about an hour afterward, and he was dressed as the person was who left the shop—I said to him, "What have you got?"—he said he had nothing but a rule, and afterwards he said he had the waistcoat.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence</hi>. The gentleman said he thought it was me. I bought it of a young man with a fustian coat; I do not know him; he came and asked me if I wanted to buy a waistcoat; I gave him 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for it; when this gentleman came, he asked me if I had got a waistcoat? I said, "Yes, a double—breasted waistcoat."</p>
